The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, July 24, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, July 23: The government today promised a host of procedural changes in the forthcoming foreign trade policy to boost project exports, now at a meagre 0.2 per cent of the $50 billion market worldwide. Realising the huge potential of project exports in India, the government has decided to propel the country in the big league by bringing in certain procedural changes shortly, commerce secretary Dipak Chatterjee said at a CII-Exim Bank seminar on Engineering Project Exports  realising the Indian potential, here.																								 New Delhi, July 23: Senior officials of the income tax department will meet here for two days from July 26 to chalk out strategies to maximise collection, reduce arrears and widen the tax base. 																								 New Delhi, July 23: Public sector oil firms will invest about Rs 17,800 crore by 2010 to produce cleaner auto-fuel compliant with Euro-III emission norms. IOC leads the pack with a planned investment of Rs 5,551 crore by March 2005.																								 Mumbai, July 23: The board of Zenith will meet on July 28 to consider proposals to demerge one of its divisions. It would also consider revaluation of assets, reduction of capital and other restructuring plans, the company said today.																								 Mumbai, July 23: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) has barred Sawaca Business Machines Ltd, its directors and associated entities from buying, selling and dealing in securities for five years.
